  "prompt": "Why does a salt solution conduct electricity?",
  "response": "A salt solution conducts electricity because of the presence of **free ions** that can carry an electric charge. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Ions:** Salts are ionic compounds. This means they are made up of positively charged ions (cations) and negatively charged ions (anions) held together by electrostatic forces.\n*   **Dissociation in Water:** When a salt dissolves in water (like sodium chloride, NaCl, in water), the water molecules break apart the ionic lattice structure of the salt. This process is called dissociation or ionization.\n*   **Free Ions:** The ions (e.g., Na+ and Cl-) become separated and move freely throughout the water. They are now hydrated (surrounded by water molecules), which helps to stabilize them in the solution.\n*   **Charge Carriers:** These free ions are now charge carriers. When a voltage is applied (e.g., by connecting electrodes to a battery), the positive ions (cations) migrate towards the negative electrode (cathode), and the negative ions (anions) migrate towards the positive electrode (anode).\n*   **Electric Current:** This movement of charged particles (ions) constitutes an electric current, allowing the salt solution to conduct electricity.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nThe ability of a salt solution to conduct electricity is due to the presence of mobile ions that are formed when the salt dissolves in water. These ions act as charge carriers, facilitating the flow of electric current through the solution.",
